<subSubSection id="812C5BB14B143799351170B7E028DB55" pageId="0" pageNumber="29" type="notes">
<paragraph id="688EDBDBA812706B794950DDC56E1E25" pageId="0" pageNumber="29">Notes.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="3F6F2043E445F21281CD0A9D20236FFF" pageId="0" pageNumber="29">
<taxonomicName id="1DBFED6FA96D02E4BEE9238262F6BDC6" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Vitaceae" genus="Vitis" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Vitis adenoclada" order="Vitales" pageId="0" pageNumber="29" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="adenoclada">
<emphasis id="459DBE77887A1E8DC59EDDF016D49856" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="29">Vitis adenoclada</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is morphologically similar to 
<taxonomicName id="F9CD74F844862AD96F8E875D3DC37FA3" genus="V." lsidName="V. heyneana" pageId="0" pageNumber="29" rank="species" species="heyneana">
<emphasis id="369662FF281BD07ACCD933DE82F59A01" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="29">V. heyneana</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
Roem. &amp; Schult, with both having arachnoid tomentose abaxial leaves. It can be easily distinguished from the latter by its red-purple glandular hairs on the young branches (vs. glandular hairs absent on young branches in 
<taxonomicName id="F4EDB5E85A43316F01E82C5224644A7E" genus="V." lsidName="V. heyneana" pageId="0" pageNumber="29" rank="species" species="heyneana">
<emphasis id="B41122BB23BEFA700D7C082D326E9EC3" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="29">V. heyneana</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
) and inflorescences usually subtended by a tendril at the base (vs. only occasionally with a tendril in 
<taxonomicName id="8585FADAB254733A18E7E1519891840D" genus="V." lsidName="V. heyneana" pageId="0" pageNumber="29" rank="species" species="heyneana">
<emphasis id="40BF3877CBD98E10B280EF8C760DD62C" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="29">V. heyneana</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
) (Figures 
<figureCitation id="5BAC2A8AFF1267CF93828F5561C55821" captionStart="Figure 1" captionStartId="F1" captionText="Figure 1. General morphology of Vitis adenoclada, especially showing the highly tomentose leaves and the inflorescences subtended by an unbranched tendril (J. Wen 11560, US)." figureDoi="10.3897/phytokeys..65519.figure1" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/556498" pageId="0" pageNumber="29">1</figureCitation>
, 
<figureCitation id="115090C2FF8143555E1E4B29CE5C7EB0" captionStart="Figure 2" captionStartId="F2" captionText="Figure 2. Characteristic glandular trichomes on young branches of Vitis adenoclada A X. Q. Liu 114 (CCAU) B X. - Q. Liu 115 (CCAU) (photo credit: Z. Y. Ma)." figureDoi="10.3897/phytokeys..65519.figure2" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/556499" pageId="0" pageNumber="29">2</figureCitation>
). 
<taxonomicName id="538B602352A5C371F1C3139A3D40EC30" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Vitaceae" genus="Vitis" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Vitis adenoclada" order="Vitales" pageId="0" pageNumber="29" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="adenoclada">
<emphasis id="9A94F779060FC9A84A204469F528FE96" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="29">Vitis adenoclada</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
may be a species of hybrid origin, with the highly tomentose 
<taxonomicName id="D1515BD2C16D0A4A321CB1072B9FA5A9" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Vitaceae" genus="Vitis" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Vitis heyneana" order="Vitales" pageId="0" pageNumber="29" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="heyneana">
<emphasis id="9E859EF865BC8F3F644592E4BA3C6658" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="29">Vitis heyneana</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
as one of the parental species, and a glandular-hair bearing 
<taxonomicName id="3A743A5F15781BD9AE0F81667B7C4FF6" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Vitaceae" genus="Vitis" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Vitis" order="Vitales" pageId="0" pageNumber="29" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="4B654FF38A612FFD2B1B92BB40D3724A" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="29">Vitis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
species, e.g., 
<taxonomicName id="D435BDE5FD29AF24CEF61F5F58D78447" genus="V." lsidName="V. romanetii" pageId="0" pageNumber="29" rank="species" species="romanetii">
<emphasis id="55B1476B4004B08705D2AC6ACEA5F25A" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="29">V. romanetii</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
Rom.Caill. or 
<taxonomicName id="79DB7528609E44A62DE6128D0295D129" genus="V." lsidName="V. davidii" pageId="0" pageNumber="29" rank="species" species="davidii">
<emphasis id="8BD5C704C1F8644ED0C2CB4E7612A181" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="29">V. davidii</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(Rom.Caill.) 
<normalizedToken id="B855D83EEF876038A947E979C1A9D974" originalValue="Foëx">Foex</normalizedToken>
as the other potential parental species. Both 
<taxonomicName id="5EE05092DF3E9D50E19D3988F4753993" genus="V." lsidName="V. davidi" pageId="0" pageNumber="29" rank="species" species="davidi">
<emphasis id="8F7796E671D836B9C3A6615298373CA4" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="29">V. davidi</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName id="6438C40C4B0877F2E64D6F57E1A24FBD" genus="V." lsidName="V. romanetii" pageId="0" pageNumber="29" rank="species" species="romanetii">
<emphasis id="9CF1C88238D1E434AB3E90FD8C90F585" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="29">V. romanetii</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
share the unique glandular trichomes with 
<taxonomicName id="8EFF7C2E6E171F8D5A8E5BF901C70A3C" genus="V." lsidName="V. adenoclada" pageId="0" pageNumber="29" rank="species" species="adenoclada">
<emphasis id="C77B9B17706B8F196D5CFF8F38122A58" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="29">V. adenoclada</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(see 
<bibRefCitation id="99B49F0ECBD6C398EF8993F5F9987E4F" DOI="https://doi.org/10.3389/fpls.2016.00704" author="Ma, ZY" journalOrPublisher="Chinese Journal of Applied and Environmental Biology" pageId="0" pageNumber="29" refId="B4" refString="Ma, ZY, Wen, J, Ickert-Bond, SM, Chen, LQ, Liu, XQ, 2016. Morphology, structure, and ontogeny of trichomes of the grape genus (Vitis, Vitaceae). Frontiers of Plant Science 7: e704. https://doi.org/10.3389/fpls.2016.00704" title="Morphology, structure, and ontogeny of trichomes of the grape genus (Vitis, Vitaceae). Frontiers of Plant Science 7: e 704." url="https://doi.org/10.3389/fpls.2016.00704" year="2016">Ma et al. 2016</bibRefCitation>
), and 
<taxonomicName id="5A485798F271FC99A06AD708D1E8A9BC" genus="V." lsidName="V. davidii" pageId="0" pageNumber="29" rank="species" species="davidii">
<emphasis id="773ED2D70C294276D83D58A559B9A3CB" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="29">V. davidii</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
occurs in southern China in the same geographic area as 
<taxonomicName id="3B34204A3ED530FD57EB9ABC41128A42" genus="V." lsidName="V. adenoclada" pageId="0" pageNumber="29" rank="species" species="adenoclada">
<emphasis id="3FAB98C8153AA688E65FF900452D2817" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="29">V. adenoclada</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. We hence regard 
<taxonomicName id="83F50437D86AAD159CEA3DD896AFE890" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Vitaceae" genus="Vitis" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Vitis davidii" order="Vitales" pageId="0" pageNumber="29" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="davidii">
<emphasis id="966DB44089123A480405B958C1662D8A" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="29">Vitis davidii</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
as a more likely parental species than 
<taxonomicName id="EFF5F26EAA148E004A15AC4F89B9E53C" genus="V." lsidName="V. romanetii" pageId="0" pageNumber="29" rank="species" species="romanetii">
<emphasis id="3EDB14928BD70311CC2B51E1F8EE3C11" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="29">V. romanetii</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
due to their geographic distribution and the highly similar glandular trichome morphology. 
<bibRefCitation id="A4437AC12B9E6841B2992EE9904060EC" DOI="https://doi.org/10.1111/jse.12444" author="Ma, ZY" journalOrPublisher="Journal of Systematics and Evolution" pageId="0" pageNumber="29" pagination="331 - 339" refId="B5" refString="Ma, ZY, Wen, J, Tian, JP, Jamal, A, Chen, LQ, Liu, XQ, 2018. Testing reticulate evolution of four Vitis species from East Asia using restriction-site associated DNA sequencing. Journal of Systematics and Evolution 56 (4): 331 - 339, DOI: https://doi.org/10.1111/jse.12444" title="Testing reticulate evolution of four Vitis species from East Asia using restriction-site associated DNA sequencing." url="https://doi.org/10.1111/jse.12444" volume="56" year="2018">Ma et al. (2018</bibRefCitation>
, 
<bibRefCitation id="4FA9221D3CB1372D690C6506E375ED25" DOI="https://doi.org/10.1016/j.ympev.2020.106809" author="Ma, ZY" journalOrPublisher="Journal of Systematics and Evolution" pageId="0" pageNumber="29" refId="B6" refString="Ma, ZY, Wen, J, Tian, JP, Gui, LL, Liu, XQ, 2020. Testing morphological trait evolution and assessing species delimitations in the grape genus using a phylogenomic framework. Molecular Phylogenetics and Evolution 148: e106809. https://doi.org/10.1016/j.ympev.2020.106809" title="Testing morphological trait evolution and assessing species delimitations in the grape genus using a phylogenomic framework. Molecular Phylogenetics and Evolution 148: e 106809." url="https://doi.org/10.1016/j.ympev.2020.106809" year="2020">2020</bibRefCitation>
) also showed that 
<taxonomicName id="42B467A27B99EC21CE6852AACB19E001" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Vitaceae" genus="Vitis" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Vitis adenoclada" order="Vitales" pageId="0" pageNumber="29" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="adenoclada">
<emphasis id="243EFF6E825FECA206B37935DE8FAD24" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="29">Vitis adenoclada</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName id="DBA6BFE69119FA05349F04CA5FA74916" genus="V." lsidName="V. davidii" pageId="0" pageNumber="29" rank="species" species="davidii">
<emphasis id="1E957A26568EBA32FF4DF5F811561750" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="29">V. davidii</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
grouped in one clade in the nuclear phylogeny, consistent with our hypothesis.
</paragraph>
